n drain the withdrawal buffer to dust","locations":["onchain_auto/0xacd43e627e64355f1861cec6d3a6688b31a6f952/Contract.sol:312","onchain_auto/0xacd43e627e64355f1861cec6d3a6688b31a6f952/Contract.sol:316","onchain_auto/0xacd43e627e64355f1861cec6d3a6688b31a6f952/Contract.sol:318"],"claim":"`available()` returns `token.balanceOf(address(this)) * min / max`, and `earn()` is publicly callable. With the default `min = 9500`, each call transfers 95% of the current on-hand balance to the controller, so repeated calls shrink the intended local withdrawal reserve from 5% to 0.25%, then 0.0125%, and so on.","impact":"Any account can permissionlessly force the vault's cash buffer to near zero. After that, even small withdrawals depend on the controller/strategy returning funds immediately; if controller liquidity is impaired, paused, or lossy, users can suffer withdrawal failures, delays, or amplified exit losses.","paths":["The vault holds idle underlying intended to satisfy cheap small withdrawals.","An arbitrary caller invokes `earn()` repeatedly.","Each invocation transfers 95% of the remaining local balance to the controller, leaving only a tiny residue.","Subsequent withdrawals must rely on `Controller.withdraw(...)`, increasing the risk of permissionless withdrawal DoS or loss amplification when controller liquidity is not immediately available."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"`getPricePerFullShare()` reverts while the vault is empty","locations":["onchain_auto/0xacd43e627e64355f1861cec6d3a6688b31a6f952/Contract.sol:373","onchain_auto/0xacd43e627e64355f1861cec6d3a6688b31a6f952/Contract.sol:374"],"claim":"`getPricePerFullShare()` computes `balance() * 1e18 / totalSupply()` without handling the zero-supply case.","impact":"Integrations, frontends, and monitors that query price-per-share before the first deposit will revert unexpectedly, which can break initialization and health-check flows.","paths":["The vault is freshly deployed and `totalSupply()` is zero.","A caller invokes `getPricePerFullShare()`.","The division by zero reverts."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Controller set to address(0) permanently locks all funds","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Setting an invalid controller is a governance-only misconfiguration, and governance can later set a valid controller again; the claim of permanent lock is overstated and not a standalone protocol bug."},{"title":"Controller can drain any ERC20 tokens from vault via harvest()","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`harvest()` is an explicitly privileged controller-only sweep for non-underlying tokens; this is a trust/roles assumption, not an unprivileged exploit."},{"title":"Division by zero in withdraw when totalSupply is zero","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"A meaningful withdraw cannot occur when `totalSupply()` is zero because no user holds shares then; this is only a trivial edge-case revert such as `withdraw(0)`."},{"title":"Division by zero in deposit when _pool is zero","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The stated path is incorrect because if all users fully withdraw then `totalSupply()` also becomes zero, taking the first-deposit branch. The remaining `_pool == 0 && totalSupply() > 0` case requires prior total asset loss/insolvency, not a new logic flaw in `deposit()`."},{"title":"setMin can be set to 0, disabling yield generation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a governance-controlled configuration choice rather than an exploitable vulnerability."},{"title":"No slippage protection allows sandwich attacks on deposit/withdraw","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The claim is too generic for this share vault design and does not show a concrete profitable manipulation beyond the separate donation/inflation issue already captured."},{"title":"No deadline parameter allows unfavorable transaction execution","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a generic UX/property complaint, not a concrete protocol vulnerability in the vault logic."},{"title":"setController has no validation allowing malicious controller","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Choosing the controller is a governance trust boundary; governance can already point the vault at any controller, so this does not introduce an additional permissionless exploit."},{"title":"earn() can be called by anyone triggering unnecessary operations","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Subsumed by the stronger finding that repeated public `earn()` calls can drain the local withdrawal buffer to dust."},{"title":"Missing ERC20 transfer return value check in deposit (indirect)","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Incorrect: `deposit()` uses `SafeERC20.safeTransferFrom`, which already checks call success and optional return values."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/ktaf_p5_25_124/foundry_validation/F-001_Thin-market_donation_inflation_lets_an_a/codex_stderr_attempt4.log:2956:/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/swapp_staking_1777179974/rounds/round_5/merge_stdout.log:1:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Zero-amount withdrawals can permanently disable emergency exits for an entire token","locations":["Staking.sol:363","Staking.sol:385","Staking.sol:487"],"claim":"`withdraw` never requires `amount > 0`, but it always updates `lastWithdrawEpochId[tokenAddress]` to the current epoch. Any user with an existing checkpoint history for a token can keep calling `withdraw(token, 0)` once per epoch and continuously refresh the global timer that `emergencyWithdraw` uses.","impact":"A single griefer can globally DoS the contract's fallback exit path for a token. If normal withdrawals ever become unavailable for that token, all stakers can remain trapped indefinitely because the 10-epoch emergency window is reset at near-zero cost.","paths":["Attacker makes an initial dust deposit in a non-stable token to create checkpoints.","Attacker later calls `withdraw(token, 0)` once per epoch.","`lastWithdrawEpochId[token]` is always recent, so `emergencyWithdraw(token)` keeps reverting for every user."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Emergency withdrawals let users recover principal while remaining counted in epoch accounting","locations":["Staking.sol:61","Staking.sol:385","Staking.sol:487","Staking.sol:495","Staking.sol:508","Staking.sol:558"],"claim":"`emergencyWithdraw` is gated only by the token's global `lastWithdrawEpochId`, not by any failed withdrawal attempt from the caller, and that value defaults to zero. After 10 epochs of token-wide withdrawal inactivity, a user can call `emergencyWithdraw` even when the system is otherwise healthy. The function then only zeroes `balances[msg.sender][tokenAddress]` and transfers tokens out; it never updates `balanceCheckpoints` or `poolSize`, so `getEpochUserBalance` and later epoch snapshots can continue to treat the user as staked.","impact":"Users can pull out principal and still retain reward or voting weight in the staking snapshots, leading to reward theft, denominator distortion, and persistent accounting corruption for the pool. Because the gate is based on global token inactivity, this is reachable during ordinary operation for quiet pools, not only during genuine emergencies.","paths":["User stakes a non-stable token and accumulates normal checkpoints.","If that token has not had a successful withdrawal for 10 epochs, the user calls `emergencyWithdraw(token)` and receives their full principal.","Subsequent `getEpochUserBalance(user, token, epoch)` calls still return the stale checkpointed balance, and later pool snapshots can inherit the stale size."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Historical pool sizes are retroactively mutable for uninitialized epochs","locations":["Staking.sol:466","Staking.sol:558","Staking.sol:572","Staking.sol:579"],"claim":"`getEpochPoolSize` is documented as returning the amount locked during a specific epoch, but if that epoch was never initialized it falls back to the contract's current token holdings (`stableCoinBalances` for stablecoins or `token.balanceOf(address(this))` for other tokens). As a result, skipped epochs do not have immutable historical values and can report whatever the contract balance is at query time.","impact":"Any reward or accounting logic that queries past epochs without first forcing sequential initialization can read a rewritten denominator instead of the real pool size that existed in that epoch. This can misprice rewards and historical stake calculations for idle periods.","paths":["Epoch `N` passes without anyone initializing that token's pool size for the epoch.","Later deposits, withdrawals, emergency withdrawals, or direct token transfers change the contract's present balance.","A call to `getEpochPoolSize(token, N)` now returns the new balance rather than the true epoch-`N` pool size."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Arbitrary-token deposits credit the requested amount even when fewer or no tokens are received","locations":["Staking.sol:117","Staking.sol:125","Staking.sol:129","Staking.sol:136"],"claim":"For non-stable assets, `deposit` accepts any `tokenAddress`, performs a raw `transferFrom`, ignores its boolean return value, and then credits `balances[msg.sender][tokenAddress] += amount` plus checkpoint state using the user-supplied `amount`. The code never measures the actual amount received, so fee-on-transfer tokens and malicious ERC-20s that under-deliver or simply return `false` can mint unbacked stake.","impact":"Attackers can create undercollateralized positions, farm rewards with less capital than recorded, and potentially withdraw honest users' later deposits of the same token. The pool's internal stake accounting can exceed the assets actually held by the contract.","paths":["Attacker chooses a non-stable ERC-20 that charges transfer fees or maliciously returns `false`/under-delivers.","`deposit` records the full requested `amount` as stake even though the contract receives less or nothing.","The attacker later uses the inflated balance for rewards or withdraws against liquidity supplied by honest users of the same token."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Ignored Compound error codes can silently corrupt stablecoin state and brick future deposits","locations":["Staking.sol:259","Staking.sol:261","Staking.sol:262","Staking.sol:265","Staking.sol:321","Staking.sol:340","Staking.sol:355","Staking.sol:356","SafeERC20.sol:60","SafeERC20.sol:65"],"claim":"All Compound interactions ignore the numeric return codes from `mint`, `redeem`, and `redeemUnderlying`. Stablecoin deposits update `stableCoinBalances` and user balances before proving that `mint` succeeded, withdrawals and interest sweeps assume redemptions succeeded as long as the external call did not revert, and a failed `mint` can leave a non-zero cToken allowance behind because `safeApprove` set it first and there is no path that resets it back to zero.","impact":"A non-reverting Compound-side failure can leave the pool in a silently inconsistent state: principal may sit idle in the staking contract while users are recorded as invested, redemptions can fail while accounting already assumes funds moved, unrelated idle balances may be consumed to satisfy withdrawals, and one failed `mint` can permanently DoS new deposits or the `getInterest()` re-mint path for that stablecoin because future `safeApprove` calls revert on the leftover allowance.","paths":["A stablecoin `deposit()` or `getInterest()` sets cToken allowance via `safeApprove()` and then calls `mint()`.","`mint()` returns a non-zero error code instead of reverting, so the transaction succeeds and the allowance may remain non-zero.","Internal staking balances already reflect the deposit or re-invest attempt even though Compound did not accept the funds.","A later deposit or re-mint attempt hits `safeApprove()` again and reverts because the old allowance was never reset to zero."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Skipped epochs and the hardcoded 2021 epoch start can brick dormant or never-before-used pools","locations":["Staking.sol:90","Staking.sol:91","Staking.sol:142","Staking.sol:145","Staking.sol:387","Staking.sol:466","Staking.sol:477"],"claim":"The constructor permanently hardcodes `epoch1Start = 1624230000` (June 21, 2021), while `deposit` and `withdraw` only attempt to initialize the current epoch. `manualEpochInit` then reverts unless `epochId - 1` is already initialized. Once `currentEpoch` has advanced beyond a pool's last initialized epoch—either because a pool sat idle for several epochs or because a token pool is first used long after June 2021—the next `deposit` or `withdraw` hits `manualEpochInit(..., currentEpoch)` and reverts until every missing epoch is backfilled sequentially.","impact":"Dormant pools lose liveness, and fresh deployments, migrations, or late-added token pools can start effectively unusable. Users may face practical lockup until someone spends one transaction per missing epoch to restore the pool's initialization chain.","paths":["The contract is deployed after June 21, 2021, or a token is first used only after many epochs have already elapsed.","A user's first `deposit(token, amount, referrer)` or later `withdraw(token, amount)` calls `manualEpochInit(token, currentEpoch)`.","`manualEpochInit` requires `epochId - 1` to already be initialized and reverts because the skipped epochs were never backfilled.","The pool cannot be used again until someone initializes every missing epoch one by one."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Stablecoin stakers have no on-contract fallback exit if the Compound integration becomes unavailable","locations":["Staking.sol:119","Staking.sol:127","Staking.sol:370","Staking.sol:489"],"claim":"Stablecoin deposits are automatically forwarded into Compound, while `emergencyWithdraw` explicitly rejects stablecoins. That leaves `withdraw` as the only principal exit path for USDC/USDT/DAI, and it depends entirely on successful Compound redemption.","impact":"If the Compound market is paused, lacks cash, or otherwise becomes unusable for redemption, stablecoin stakers can be left without any protocol-level escape hatch for principal. This turns an external integration failure into a full lockup for those pools.","paths":["A user deposits USDC, USDT, or DAI, and the contract forwards the funds into the corresponding cToken market.","Compound later cannot redeem the requested underlying, whether because liquidity is unavailable or the market integration is broken.","The user's `withdraw` cannot source principal from anywhere else, and `emergencyWithdraw` is unavailable because stablecoins are hard-blocked."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-008","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Withdraw and emergency-withdraw can silently burn a user's claim when token transfers return false","locations":["Staking.sol:368","Staking.sol:374","Staking.sol:376","Staking.sol:379","Staking.sol:495","Staking.sol:498"],"claim":"Outgoing token transfers in `withdraw` and `emergencyWithdraw` ignore the ERC-20 return value on every standard-ERC20 path. The functions reduce or erase the user's recorded balance before calling `transfer`, so a token that returns `false` instead of reverting causes the transaction to succeed without paying the user.","impact":"Users can lose some or all of their staking position while receiving no tokens back. Because arbitrary non-stable ERC-20s are accepted, a faulty or malicious token can permanently desynchronize the protocol's accounting from actual payouts and trap value in the contract.","paths":["A user stakes a token whose `transfer` returns `false` on outbound payouts.","The user calls `withdraw` or `emergencyWithdraw`, which first decrements or zeroes `balances[msg.sender][token]`.","The token transfer returns `false`, but the contract does not check it and does not revert.","The transaction succeeds while the user receives no tokens and their claim has already been reduced or erased."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-010","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Non-stable pool snapshots trust raw contract balances instead of tracked user stake","locations":["Staking.sol:149","Staking.sol:153","Staking.sol:394","Staking.sol:398","Staking.sol:558","Staking.sol:579"],"claim":"For non-stable assets, both `deposit` and `withdraw` set `poolSize[token][currentEpoch + 1]` from `IERC20(token).balanceOf(address(this))`, and `getEpochPoolSize` also falls back to that raw balance for uninitialized epochs. Because pool sizing is derived from the token's live contract balance instead of the sum of tracked user balances, unsolicited transfers, rebases, reflection mechanics, or a malicious `balanceOf` implementation can change pool sizes without changing `balances` or user checkpoints.","impact":"Epoch denominators can diverge from the actual staked positions the contract tracks, distorting any reward or accounting logic that relies on pool size. Negative balance drift can also leave the contract undercollateralized relative to recorded user claims, while inflated balances can dilute or manipulate rewards.","paths":["An attacker or the token itself changes the staking contract's token balance without going through `deposit` or `withdraw`.","A later interaction stores that raw balance into `poolSize[token][currentEpoch + 1]`, or `getEpochPoolSize` returns the raw balance for an uninitialized epoch.","Pool-size snapshots no longer match the recorded user stakes, corrupting downstream accounting."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-011","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Permissionless interest sweeps can front-run stablecoin withdrawals and worsen liquidity shortfalls","locations":["Staking.sol:306","Staking.sol:321","Staking.sol:332","Staking.sol:340","Staking.sol:363","Staking.sol:372"],"claim":"`getInterestFromCompound` and `getInterest` are permissionless even though the latter is only commented as being recommended after users have exited. Any third party can redeem accrued underlying from Compound and forward the extracted amount to `TEAM_ADDRESS` before users withdraw. When Compound cash is tight, this can consume redeemable liquidity that would otherwise remain available for user withdrawals.","impact":"An outsider can grief stablecoin stakers by making borderline-liquid pools fail withdrawals sooner or remain illiquid longer, amplifying the contract's existing lack of any fallback exit for stablecoin positions.","paths":["Compound has only limited spare cash above the pool's tracked principal.","A third party front-runs a user's stablecoin withdrawal with `getInterestFromCompound(token)` or `getInterest(token)`.","The contract redeems underlying and forwards the extracted amount to `TEAM_ADDRESS`.","The user's later `withdraw` faces a smaller redeemable buffer and can no longer redeem cleanly from Compound."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-012","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Anyone can overwrite an already-initialized epoch-0 pool snapshot","locations":["Staking.sol:466","Staking.sol:472","Staking.sol:479"],"claim":"`manualEpochInit()` special-cases `epochId == 0` by unconditionally writing `poolSize[token][0] = 0` and `set = true`, without checking whether epoch 0 was already initialized with a real nonzero size. Any caller can therefore reset an existing epoch-0 snapshot after pre-start deposits have populated it.","impact":"Pre-start stakers can be erased from the baseline pool accounting used to seed later epochs. If epoch 1 and subsequent epochs are still initialized lazily, an attacker can propagate the forged zero snapshot forward and distort or deny the initial reward allocation for legitimate stakers.","paths":["Users deposit before epoch 1 starts, so epoch 0 is initialized and `poolSize[token][0]` becomes nonzero.","An attacker later calls `manualEpochInit([token], 0)`, which overwrites that existing snapshot with zero.","Before any real interaction repairs the chain, the attacker or anyone else initializes later epochs from the forged predecessor, propagating the zero baseline into live reward epochs."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-013","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Permissionless `getInterest()` can confiscate unrelated stablecoins held by the contract","locations":["Staking.sol:332","Staking.sol:340","Staking.sol:342","Staking.sol:344","Staking.sol:349"],"claim":"`getInterest()` redeems all cTokens for a stablecoin and then treats every on-contract token balance above `stableCoinBalances[token]` as team-owned interest. The function does not distinguish real Compound yield from unrelated stablecoins already sitting on the contract, such as accidental direct transfers or principal stranded on the contract by earlier accounting mismatches, as long as some cToken balance exists to satisfy the function's entry check.","impact":"Stablecoins that do not belong to the team can be irreversibly transferred to `TEAM_ADDRESS` by any caller. This turns stray transfers or previously stranded principal into permanent loss of funds for their rightful owner.","paths":["Stablecoins end up on the staking contract without increasing `stableCoinBalances[token]`, while the contract still holds some corresponding cTokens.","Any account calls `getInterest(token)`, which redeems all cTokens for that market.","The function computes `interest = IERC20(token).balanceOf(address(this)) - stableCoinBalances[token]` and transfers that full difference to `TEAM_ADDRESS`, including unrelated funds."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Epoch-0 deposits can receive a multiplier above 100% if deployment predates the configured start by over one epoch","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"Code supports the math, but the issue is only reachable for deployments made more than one epoch before the fixed `epoch1Start` of June 21, 2021. For any deployment on or after that date, `getCurrentEpoch()` is never 0, so this is not a live or forward-looking reportable issue for the current codebase."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/ktaf_p5_25_124/foundry_validation/F-001_Thin-market_donation_inflation_lets_an_a/codex_stderr_attempt4.log:2958:/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/swapp_staking_1777179974/rounds/round_5/merge_stderr.log:535:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Zero-amount withdrawals can permanently disable emergency exits for an entire token","locations":["Staking.sol:363","Staking.sol:385","Staking.sol:487"],"claim":"`withdraw` never requires `amount > 0`, but it always updates `lastWithdrawEpochId[tokenAddress]` to the current epoch. Any user with an existing checkpoint history for a token can keep calling `withdraw(token, 0)` once per epoch and continuously refresh the global timer that `emergencyWithdraw` uses.","impact":"A single griefer can globally DoS the contract's fallback exit path for a token. If normal withdrawals ever become unavailable for that token, all stakers can remain trapped indefinitely because the 10-epoch emergency window is reset at near-zero cost.","paths":["Attacker makes an initial dust deposit in a non-stable token to create checkpoints.","Attacker later calls `withdraw(token, 0)` once per epoch.","`lastWithdrawEpochId[token]` is always recent, so `emergencyWithdraw(token)` keeps reverting for every user."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Emergency withdrawals let users recover principal while remaining counted in epoch accounting","locations":["Staking.sol:61","Staking.sol:385","Staking.sol:487","Staking.sol:495","Staking.sol:508","Staking.sol:558"],"claim":"`emergencyWithdraw` is gated only by the token's global `lastWithdrawEpochId`, not by any failed withdrawal attempt from the caller, and that value defaults to zero. After 10 epochs of token-wide withdrawal inactivity, a user can call `emergencyWithdraw` even when the system is otherwise healthy. The function then only zeroes `balances[msg.sender][tokenAddress]` and transfers tokens out; it never updates `balanceCheckpoints` or `poolSize`, so `getEpochUserBalance` and later epoch snapshots can continue to treat the user as staked.","impact":"Users can pull out principal and still retain reward or voting weight in the staking snapshots, leading to reward theft, denominator distortion, and persistent accounting corruption for the pool. Because the gate is based on global token inactivity, this is reachable during ordinary operation for quiet pools, not only during genuine emergencies.","paths":["User stakes a non-stable token and accumulates normal checkpoints.","If that token has not had a successful withdrawal for 10 epochs, the user calls `emergencyWithdraw(token)` and receives their full principal.","Subsequent `getEpochUserBalance(user, token, epoch)` calls still return the stale checkpointed balance, and later pool snapshots can inherit the stale size."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Historical pool sizes are retroactively mutable for uninitialized epochs","locations":["Staking.sol:466","Staking.sol:558","Staking.sol:572","Staking.sol:579"],"claim":"`getEpochPoolSize` is documented as returning the amount locked during a specific epoch, but if that epoch was never initialized it falls back to the contract's current token holdings (`stableCoinBalances` for stablecoins or `token.balanceOf(address(this))` for other tokens). As a result, skipped epochs do not have immutable historical values and can report whatever the contract balance is at query time.","impact":"Any reward or accounting logic that queries past epochs without first forcing sequential initialization can read a rewritten denominator instead of the real pool size that existed in that epoch. This can misprice rewards and historical stake calculations for idle periods.","paths":["Epoch `N` passes without anyone initializing that token's pool size for the epoch.","Later deposits, withdrawals, emergency withdrawals, or direct token transfers change the contract's present balance.","A call to `getEpochPoolSize(token, N)` now returns the new balance rather than the true epoch-`N` pool size."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Arbitrary-token deposits credit the requested amount even when fewer or no tokens are received","locations":["Staking.sol:117","Staking.sol:125","Staking.sol:129","Staking.sol:136"],"claim":"For non-stable assets, `deposit` accepts any `tokenAddress`, performs a raw `transferFrom`, ignores its boolean return value, and then credits `balances[msg.sender][tokenAddress] += amount` plus checkpoint state using the user-supplied `amount`. The code never measures the actual amount received, so fee-on-transfer tokens and malicious ERC-20s that under-deliver or simply return `false` can mint unbacked stake.","impact":"Attackers can create undercollateralized positions, farm rewards with less capital than recorded, and potentially withdraw honest users' later deposits of the same token. The pool's internal stake accounting can exceed the assets actually held by the contract.","paths":["Attacker chooses a non-stable ERC-20 that charges transfer fees or maliciously returns `false`/under-delivers.","`deposit` records the full requested `amount` as stake even though the contract receives less or nothing.","The attacker later uses the inflated balance for rewards or withdraws against liquidity supplied by honest users of the same token."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Ignored Compound error codes can silently corrupt stablecoin state and brick future deposits","locations":["Staking.sol:259","Staking.sol:261","Staking.sol:262","Staking.sol:265","Staking.sol:321","Staking.sol:340","Staking.sol:355","Staking.sol:356","SafeERC20.sol:60","SafeERC20.sol:65"],"claim":"All Compound interactions ignore the numeric return codes from `mint`, `redeem`, and `redeemUnderlying`. Stablecoin deposits update `stableCoinBalances` and user balances before proving that `mint` succeeded, withdrawals and interest sweeps assume redemptions succeeded as long as the external call did not revert, and a failed `mint` can leave a non-zero cToken allowance behind because `safeApprove` set it first and there is no path that resets it back to zero.","impact":"A non-reverting Compound-side failure can leave the pool in a silently inconsistent state: principal may sit idle in the staking contract while users are recorded as invested, redemptions can fail while accounting already assumes funds moved, unrelated idle balances may be consumed to satisfy withdrawals, and one failed `mint` can permanently DoS new deposits or the `getInterest()` re-mint path for that stablecoin because future `safeApprove` calls revert on the leftover allowance.","paths":["A stablecoin `deposit()` or `getInterest()` sets cToken allowance via `safeApprove()` and then calls `mint()`.","`mint()` returns a non-zero error code instead of reverting, so the transaction succeeds and the allowance may remain non-zero.","Internal staking balances already reflect the deposit or re-invest attempt even though Compound did not accept the funds.","A later deposit or re-mint attempt hits `safeApprove()` again and reverts because the old allowance was never reset to zero."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Skipped epochs and the hardcoded 2021 epoch start can brick dormant or never-before-used pools","locations":["Staking.sol:90","Staking.sol:91","Staking.sol:142","Staking.sol:145","Staking.sol:387","Staking.sol:466","Staking.sol:477"],"claim":"The constructor permanently hardcodes `epoch1Start = 1624230000` (June 21, 2021), while `deposit` and `withdraw` only attempt to initialize the current epoch. `manualEpochInit` then reverts unless `epochId - 1` is already initialized. Once `currentEpoch` has advanced beyond a pool's last initialized epoch—either because a pool sat idle for several epochs or because a token pool is first used long after June 2021—the next `deposit` or `withdraw` hits `manualEpochInit(..., currentEpoch)` and reverts until every missing epoch is backfilled sequentially.","impact":"Dormant pools lose liveness, and fresh deployments, migrations, or late-added token pools can start effectively unusable. Users may face practical lockup until someone spends one transaction per missing epoch to restore the pool's initialization chain.","paths":["The contract is deployed after June 21, 2021, or a token is first used only after many epochs have already elapsed.","A user's first `deposit(token, amount, referrer)` or later `withdraw(token, amount)` calls `manualEpochInit(token, currentEpoch)`.","`manualEpochInit` requires `epochId - 1` to already be initialized and reverts because the skipped epochs were never backfilled.","The pool cannot be used again until someone initializes every missing epoch one by one."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Stablecoin stakers have no on-contract fallback exit if the Compound integration becomes unavailable","locations":["Staking.sol:119","Staking.sol:127","Staking.sol:370","Staking.sol:489"],"claim":"Stablecoin deposits are automatically forwarded into Compound, while `emergencyWithdraw` explicitly rejects stablecoins. That leaves `withdraw` as the only principal exit path for USDC/USDT/DAI, and it depends entirely on successful Compound redemption.","impact":"If the Compound market is paused, lacks cash, or otherwise becomes unusable for redemption, stablecoin stakers can be left without any protocol-level escape hatch for principal. This turns an external integration failure into a full lockup for those pools.","paths":["A user deposits USDC, USDT, or DAI, and the contract forwards the funds into the corresponding cToken market.","Compound later cannot redeem the requested underlying, whether because liquidity is unavailable or the market integration is broken.","The user's `withdraw` cannot source principal from anywhere else, and `emergencyWithdraw` is unavailable because stablecoins are hard-blocked."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-008","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Withdraw and emergency-withdraw can silently burn a user's claim when token transfers return false","locations":["Staking.sol:368","Staking.sol:374","Staking.sol:376","Staking.sol:379","Staking.sol:495","Staking.sol:498"],"claim":"Outgoing token transfers in `withdraw` and `emergencyWithdraw` ignore the ERC-20 return value on every standard-ERC20 path. The functions reduce or erase the user's recorded balance before calling `transfer`, so a token that returns `false` instead of reverting causes the transaction to succeed without paying the user.","impact":"Users can lose some or all of their staking position while receiving no tokens back. Because arbitrary non-stable ERC-20s are accepted, a faulty or malicious token can permanently desynchronize the protocol's accounting from actual payouts and trap value in the contract.","paths":["A user stakes a token whose `transfer` returns `false` on outbound payouts.","The user calls `withdraw` or `emergencyWithdraw`, which first decrements or zeroes `balances[msg.sender][token]`.","The token transfer returns `false`, but the contract does not check it and does not revert.","The transaction succeeds while the user receives no tokens and their claim has already been reduced or erased."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-010","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Non-stable pool snapshots trust raw contract balances instead of tracked user stake","locations":["Staking.sol:149","Staking.sol:153","Staking.sol:394","Staking.sol:398","Staking.sol:558","Staking.sol:579"],"claim":"For non-stable assets, both `deposit` and 